# {{ .ProjectName }}

Generated by `gos`.

## 1. Quick start

```bash
go run ./cmd/api serve
go run ./cmd/api schedule
go run ./cmd/api queue
gofmt -l .
go test ./...
go vet ./...
go build ./cmd/api
```

Health check:

```bash
curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/healthz
```

`go run ./cmd/api` defaults to `serve`. Commands are implemented with Cobra. `schedule` and `queue` are executable worker entrypoints backed by `internal/worker`, which provides common lifecycle logging, periodic execution, error logging, and panic recovery.

`Makefile` is included as an optional convenience only. The project does not require a local `make` command.

## 2. Project layout

```text
cmd/api                          API entrypoint
api/openapi.yaml                 HTTP contract
internal/command                 CLI command scripts generated by gos
internal/app                     dependency assembly and application lifecycle
internal/config                  environment configuration
internal/domain                  entities, domain errors, repository contracts
internal/usecase                 application usecases
internal/interfaces/http         router, handlers, middleware, HTTP error mapping
internal/infrastructure/database database/sql connection and transaction manager
internal/infrastructure/persistence/mysql
                                  MySQL repository implementations
internal/worker                  scheduled job and queue worker lifecycle helpers
internal/pkg/apperror            application errors
internal/pkg/response            JSON response helpers
deployments/docker               Dockerfile and Compose files
migrations                       SQL migrations generated by gos
```

Dependency direction:

```text
handler -> usecase -> domain
mysql repository -> domain
app -> wires config, database, repositories, usecases, handlers
```

## 3. Commands

The generated binary supports subcommands:

```bash
go run ./cmd/api serve
go run ./cmd/api schedule
go run ./cmd/api queue
go run ./cmd/api help
```

Add a project Cobra command:

```bash
gos make:command sync-orders --register
go run ./cmd/api sync-orders
```

## 4. CI

GitHub Actions workflow is defined at `.github/workflows/ci.yml`.

It checks formatting with `gofmt`, runs `go vet ./...`, runs `go test ./...`, and builds `./cmd/api`.

If MySQL repositories exist, CI also runs integration tests against a MySQL service.

## 5. Docker

```bash
docker build -f deployments/docker/Dockerfile -t {{ .AppName }} .
docker compose -f deployments/docker/docker-compose.yml up --build
```

Docker Compose includes the API service, MySQL, and Redis for local development.

## 6. Configuration

Configuration is read from environment variables into `internal/config.Config`.

```text
APP_NAME
APP_ENV
HTTP_ADDR
HTTP_READ_HEADER_TIMEOUT
HTTP_READ_TIMEOUT
HTTP_WRITE_TIMEOUT
HTTP_IDLE_TIMEOUT
HTTP_MAX_HEADER_BYTES
HTTP_MAX_BODY_BYTES
CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS
CORS_ALLOWED_METHODS
CORS_ALLOWED_HEADERS
CORS_ALLOW_CREDENTIALS
CORS_MAX_AGE
DB_DRIVER
DB_DSN
DB_ENABLE_NESTED_TRANSACTION
REDIS_ADDR
REDIS_PASSWORD
REDIS_DB
LOG_LEVEL
{{- if .WithOpenTelemetry }}
OTEL_ENABLED
OTEL_SERVICE_NAME
OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT
OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_INSECURE
{{- end }}
```

MySQL support is registered through `github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql`. Leave `DB_DSN` empty to run without a database connection, or set `DB_DRIVER=mysql` and a MySQL DSN to enable startup-time connection checks.

Example:

```bash
DB_DRIVER=mysql
DB_DSN='root:password@tcp(127.0.0.1:3306)/{{ .AppName }}?parseTime=true'
DB_ENABLE_NESTED_TRANSACTION=false
```

Application and usecase code should receive configuration through constructors or assembled dependencies, not by calling `os.Getenv` directly.

Logging is initialized from `internal/logging` during startup. `LOG_LEVEL` supports `debug`, `info`, `warn`, `warning`, and `error`; logs are emitted as JSON to stdout. Sensitive field keys such as `password`, `token`, `authorization`, `secret`, and `dsn` are redacted by default.{{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }} When tracing is enabled, log records automatically include `trace_id` and `span_id` when the current context carries a valid span.{{ end }}

Boolean, integer, int64, and duration environment variables are parsed strictly. Invalid values such as `REDIS_DB=abc`, `DB_ENABLE_NESTED_TRANSACTION=maybe`, or `HTTP_READ_TIMEOUT=abc` fail during startup instead of silently falling back to defaults. `HTTP_MAX_BODY_BYTES=0` disables request body size limiting.

CORS is configured through `CORS_*` environment variables. Production deployments should set `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS` to explicit domains instead of using `*`, especially when enabling credentials.
