## 7. Observability

OpenTelemetry tracing support is included but disabled by default.

```bash
OTEL_ENABLED=false
OTEL_SERVICE_NAME={{ .AppName }}
OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT=localhost:4318
OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_INSECURE=true
```

When enabled, startup configures an OTLP HTTP trace exporter, wraps the HTTP router with `otelhttp`, provides a traced HTTP client helper, and opens database/sql connections through `github.com/XSAM/otelsql`.
{{ end }}

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}8{{ else }}7{{ end }}. API contract

The default HTTP contract starts at `api/openapi.yaml`.

Recommended flow:

```text
1. Update OpenAPI first.
2. Implement or generate the handler.
3. Keep request and response DTOs aligned with the contract.
4. Add handler tests for status codes and response shape.
```

`gos make:handler <module> --openapi` can append a list path with tags, a list success response, and standard error response references. Complex request bodies, domain schemas, and business-specific error codes should still be reviewed manually.

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}9{{ else }}8{{ end }}. HTTP layer

Router entrypoint:

```text
internal/interfaces/http/router.go
```

Default middleware:

```text
RequestID
Recover
CORS
AccessLog
Timeout
```

Generate a handler:

```bash
gos make:handler invoice --register --openapi
```

Handler responsibilities:

```text
1. Decode path, query, and request body.
2. Call usecases.
3. Convert outputs to response.JSON.
4. Map errors through httperror.
```

Do not put core business logic or SQL in handlers.

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}10{{ else }}9{{ end }}. Usecase layer

Generate a usecase:

```bash
gos make:usecase invoice/create
```

Usecases should own business flow and transaction boundaries. They should depend on small interfaces, making unit tests easy to write with fakes.

Example transaction boundary:

```go
func (uc *CreateUsecase) Execute(ctx context.Context, input CreateInput) (*CreateOutput, error) {
	if err := ctx.Err(); err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}

	var id int64
	err := uc.transactions.WithinTx(ctx, func(ctx context.Context) error {
		invoice := &domain.Invoice{
			Number: input.Number,
			Total:  input.Total,
		}
		if err := uc.invoices.Save(ctx, invoice); err != nil {
			return err
		}
		id = invoice.ID
		return nil
	})
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}

	return &CreateOutput{ID: id}, nil
}
```

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}11{{ else }}10{{ end }}. Domain layer

Domain code lives under `internal/domain/<module>`.

Generate an entity only:

```bash
gos make:model invoice --fields=number:string,total:int64,created_at:time
```

Best practices:

```text
1. Put business invariants and domain errors close to the entity.
2. Keep domain independent from HTTP, SQL, Redis, and environment variables.
3. Use stable errors so upper layers can use errors.Is.
```

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}12{{ else }}11{{ end }}. Repository layer

Generate a MySQL repository:

```bash
gos make:repository invoice --fields=number:string:unique,size=64,total:int64,paid:bool,created_at:time:default=now --with-migration --register
```

Generated repository methods:

```text
FindByID(ctx, id)
Save(ctx, entity)
DeleteByID(ctx, id)
```

`Save` inserts when `ID == 0`, updates when `ID != 0`, and fills the generated ID after insert.

Repositories use:

```go
executor := database.ExecutorFromContext(ctx, r.db)
```

This makes repository methods automatically participate in the current transaction when the context contains one.

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}13{{ else }}12{{ end }}. Transactions

Transaction manager:

```text
internal/infrastructure/database/transaction.go
```

Use transactions from usecases:

```go
err := txManager.WithinTx(ctx, func(ctx context.Context) error {
	if err := orderRepo.Save(ctx, order); err != nil {
		return err
	}
	return inventoryRepo.Save(ctx, inventory)
})
```

Default nested behavior:

```text
DB_ENABLE_NESTED_TRANSACTION=false
```

When a transaction already exists in context, inner `WithinTx` calls reuse the outer transaction.

Savepoint mode:

```text
DB_ENABLE_NESTED_TRANSACTION=true
```

In this mode, inner `WithinTx` calls create `SAVEPOINT`, release it on success, and roll back to it on failure. The outer transaction still controls the final commit.

Keep this disabled unless the business case needs local rollback inside a larger transaction.

