## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}15{{ else }}14{{ end }}. Tests

Regular tests:

```bash
go test ./...
```

Repository integration tests generated by `gos make:repository` use the `integration` build tag and `TEST_DATABASE_DSN`.

```bash
docker compose -f deployments/docker/docker-compose.test.yml up -d
TEST_DATABASE_DSN='root:password@tcp(127.0.0.1:3307)/{{ .AppName }}_test?parseTime=true' go test -tags=integration ./internal/infrastructure/persistence/mysql
```

Without `TEST_DATABASE_DSN`, generated repository integration tests are skipped.

PowerShell:

```powershell
$env:TEST_DATABASE_DSN='root:password@tcp(127.0.0.1:3307)/{{ .AppName }}_test?parseTime=true'
go test -tags=integration ./internal/infrastructure/persistence/mysql
```

Recommended testing split:

```text
1. Domain rules: unit tests.
2. Usecases: unit tests with fake dependencies.
3. Handlers: httptest status and response assertions.
4. Repositories: integration tests against MySQL.
```

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}16{{ else }}15{{ end }}. Dependency assembly

Application dependencies are assembled in `internal/app/assembly.go`.

Use that file to wire repositories, usecases, handlers, queues, storage clients, and other infrastructure implementations with explicit constructors.

`gos make:repository <module> --register` can update repository wiring markers automatically. Usecase and handler wiring should remain explicit and easy to read.

## {{ if .WithOpenTelemetry }}17{{ else }}16{{ end }}. Best practices

```text
1. Keep handlers thin.
2. Put transaction boundaries in usecases.
3. Keep repositories focused on persistence.
4. Keep domain independent from frameworks and infrastructure.
5. Prefer constructor injection over global variables.
6. Review generated migrations before applying them.
7. Run go test ./... after generation and after manual edits.
8. Use --dry-run before generating into an existing codebase.
9. Avoid --force on files that already contain hand-written business logic.
```
